      "content": "You are right to point out the historical record, as nationalism has been a primary justification for conflict and oppression. The very act of defining who belongs and who doesn't inherently creates an \"other\" that can be dehumanized. Therefore, while it offers a sense of belonging, its inherent tendency toward in-group favoritism makes it a fundamental obstacle to universal human rights and global peace. It is a deeply flawed ideology that requires constant, rigorous self-correction to avoid becoming destructive.",
